<p class="c32"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 624.00px; height: 4.00px;"><img alt="" src="images/image1.png" style="width: 624.00px; height: 4.00px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title="horizontal line"></span></p>
</div><h2 class="c27" id="h.4dg39on44gn9"><span class="c35 c37 c12">Summer, Year 2</span></h2><h2 class="c27" id="h.4g2aeewbwa7r"><span class="c29 c12">ccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccc</span></h2><p class="c6"><span class="c2">A powerful wind blows over the mountainside. &nbsp;It blows open a shuttered window, allowing the summer sun to beam directly onto you. &nbsp;The last time, you had the energy to close it again. &nbsp;This time, you only are able to hate it. &nbsp;You hate it, want it to die, and also kind of want to die as well.</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">You are&hellip; Shit. &nbsp;No, wait, you aren&rsquo;t shit. &nbsp;You&rsquo;re just&hellip; who the fuck are you again? &nbsp;Hang on, let&rsquo;s go through the checklist.</span></p>
<ol class="c19 lst-kix_zf4sdwv6y44s-0 start" start="1"><li class="c6 c20"><span class="c2">You immediately started thinking in a checklist. &nbsp;You&rsquo;re probably a pretty organized guy.</span></li><li class="c6 c20"><span class="c2">Fuck you. &nbsp;You&rsquo;re also a pretty rude guy, you guess.</span></li><li class="c6 c20"><span class="c2">You&rsquo;re a guy, at least you&rsquo;re pretty sure you are, so that cuts your options down for who you are significantly.</span></li></ol><p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c16 c18">Based on these three factors alone, you&rsquo;re about 90% confident that you are </span><span class="c16 c12">Renyan</span><span class="c2">, that guy who others think is so smart they named him the first one to have to deal with this oxshit.</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Oh judgemental ancestors, it&rsquo;s coming back to you now. &nbsp;Yes, you are the First Among Scholars&hellip; huh, it doesn&rsquo;t bold when you&rsquo;ve already been identified&hellip; and you have been having a really weird, uh, last three months.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Lots of discoveries there. &nbsp;Lots of ups and downs. &nbsp;Probably the biggest down was when you were about to suggest selectively culling the population, and then that big&hellip; big&hellip; biggy bigelf went and took all of that courage you were mustering up and threw it directly off the mountain, upstaging you at the part where you were going to turn history.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">That was pretty bad. &nbsp;Yep. &nbsp;Pretty bad.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">But then there was the weird bit that when the Aggro started actually doing that thing they said they would do, they actually put in some effort to scope the place properly, and inadvertently totally validated your theory that the lowlands could have exploitable agriculture land. &nbsp;If only someone competent had been sent the first time around, a lot of shit around here would be pretty different. &nbsp;That was&hellip; kinda good? &nbsp;In an I-Told-You-So sort of way? Of course, then they started ripping it to shreds. &nbsp;Not great.</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c16 c18">But then, thinking of agriculture, after that display, the heads pretty much totally ignored your plan to make new dirt. &nbsp;Instead, they kept following up on the things they were doing. &nbsp;It was pretty bad that you got ignored, you took that one kind of hard, but really, that was a net positive all things considered; they not only totally validated your theories- yes, you were 100% correct, even pretty much about the pad-time needed- they also got motivated to figure out ways to make it go faster, AND even, on their own initiative, worked with the Samra and Onagi to make more of those quartz...things. &nbsp;That&rsquo;s Really a plus, because those sad sacks of shit weren&rsquo;t doing </span><span class="c16 c18 c5">anything</span><span class="c16 c18">&nbsp;before you whipped them into action, so you can pretty much take credit for this new burst of energy! </span><span class="c16 c18 c5">Nice</span><span class="c2">! &nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c16 c18">Although, speaking of the Onagi, then there&rsquo;s the fact that the Layer of the Path, who you really wanted to try to coordinate with for your soil-making plan, just kind of...disappeared. &nbsp;Which had you really stressed out for a lot of reasons that are difficult to articulate, especially right now. &nbsp;You were pretty sure she wasn&rsquo;t </span><span class="c16 c18 c5">definitely</span><span class="c2">&nbsp;dead, since when you actually broke down and asked the old crone about it, she said not to concern yourself and to tend to your own tasks, which probably at least meant she knew what was going on. &nbsp;Still, given her track record of late, that tidbit was a pretty strong down force through the season.</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">But hey, at least progress was being made! &nbsp;So as long as the Aggro kept bringing in the food, you could keep the fields fallow, let the Blight die off, and then everything would be back to normal!</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">That&rsquo;s when they set the entire world on fire.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Or, at least, it kind of seemed like it. &nbsp;The smoke was so big and high you could see it from your workplace. &nbsp;That was a pretty bad week. &nbsp;Without that supply of food, the whole fallow plan was pretty screwed. &nbsp;It would even be too late for your original plan. &nbsp;That was kind of a combined &ldquo;aw shit&rdquo; and &ldquo;I told you so&rdquo;, so really mixed bag.</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">And then the mixed bags arrived. &nbsp;Whoo boy.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">The Layer of the Path came back! +<br>She brought an absurd amount of food! ++<br>The food came from Lowlander elves. --</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Who she pretty much had to tell about Eschaton.---<br>And probably where it&rsquo;s located.----</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">And the whole thing was the Esteemed&rsquo;s idea, so basically her farsighted wisdom saved the day.------------</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Probably while dooming you all. +?</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">That&rsquo;s when you decided to...</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">&nbsp;consult the Spirits of the Ancients.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Well, one ancient in particular. &nbsp;Sivens. &nbsp;Tedious shit that he was, he still gave you a stoppered decanter of fermented&hellip; something&hellip; the first time you tried to take the Elemat Bloodname from him. &nbsp;And failed. A consolation prize. &nbsp;You preferred to use it as your Totem of Unbridled Ire. &nbsp;The inherent patronizing nature of it kept you studying and honing your mind long into the nights. &nbsp;He certainly didn&rsquo;t give you one the next time you invoked Bloodrite. In fact, you never saw him again. &nbsp;You heard a building fell on him. &nbsp;It sort of disappointed you that his death wasn&rsquo;t ironic in any way.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">That decanter&rsquo;s empty now. &nbsp; Since the whole world was going mad, it just made sense to join them the best way you could.</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">...You really do have to say, for a guy with what is probably a splitting hangover, you&rsquo;re holding up pretty well on the cognition front. &nbsp;Wait. Do you actually have a hangover?</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">You crack open an eye. &nbsp;The sun is bright, check that, ow, but not really causing any splitting headache. &nbsp;How&hellip;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">You open both your eyes- looking to the side this time, clever you- and rediscover what you&rsquo;ve been rediscovering for, by your estimate, the last week worth of mornings in a row.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c16 c18">A collection of vials, four of them empty, one full, labeled </span><span class="c16 c18 c5">Drink this</span><span class="c16 c18">. &nbsp;In smaller text beneath, </span><span class="c16 c18 c5">No, really.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Sivens&rsquo; final lesson, tucked in small scroll at the bottom of the decanter. &nbsp;Probably intended to keep you from challenging him again, considering the consequences, although you bet he wasn&rsquo;t planning for you to almost choke to death on it.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c16 c18">&nbsp; A simple little alchemical formula for something whimsically called a </span><span class="c16 c18 c5">Polypurpose Panacea</span><span class="c2">. &nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">You grab the vial of pink viscous liquid and hammer it back, muscle memory knowing what your state-dependent doesn&rsquo;t. </span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c16 c18 c5">Time to get shit done.</span></p>
<hr><p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">The expanse of Eschaton sweeps beneath you. &nbsp;From here, even the Pagoda of the Esteemed is beneath your gaze. &nbsp;You had discovered this particular outcropping as a youth, and visited it frequently; the panorama it provided always seemed to calm you. &nbsp;Even from here, the boundaries of the Greatest of the Crag settlements cannot be taken in a single eyeful. When you are younger, the sight of it filled you with calm and awe.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c16 c18">Now, having traversed the Floor of the World, the great expanse of the Lowlands, and all the mysterious dangers that lurk within, all you can think of is how </span><span class="c16 c18 c5">boring </span><span class="c2">it is. &nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Speaking of boring, you figure now is as good a time as any for repast. &nbsp;While still perched and observing, you deftly fish into your sidepouch, pulling forth another curious gift of the Lowlands. &nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c16 c18">To your understanding, the tuber was called a &lsquo;Potato&rsquo;. &nbsp;There was some disagreement as to whether that was </span><span class="c16 c18">po-tah-to or po-tay-to</span><span class="c2">, but what could not be disagreed with was it&rsquo;s utility as a marching ration. &nbsp;You&rsquo;d estimate that one of these brown spheroids contained as much packed energy and nutrition as any cliff rye cracker, if not moreso.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">You bite into the thick root with a resounding crunch.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c16 c18">Shame about the taste, though.</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">As you chew, you consider your next course of action carefully. &nbsp;You observe your next destination, your next target, with keen eyes, trying to imagine the sequence of events to follow. &nbsp;With practiced stillness, ingrained from over a hundred successful hunts, you tend to the needs of your flesh while your mind is free to plan, to prepare, and to foresee. Through this talent, one of the chief skills in a Stalker&rsquo;s retinue, you can determine one thing with utmost surety.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">You are stalling.</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c16 c18">You are </span><span class="c16 c12">Embebi</span><span class="c16 c18">, and if you&rsquo;re being honest with yourself, you&rsquo;ve kind of been stalling for nearly the past week. &nbsp;When you returned to Eschaton from the Esteemed&rsquo;s bizzare, but not totally unwelcome, mission into the depths of the Lowlands, you were almost- </span><span class="c16 c18 c5">almost</span><span class="c16 c18">, not actually, but </span><span class="c16 c18 c5">almost</span><span class="c2">- grateful for the disaster which had struck in your absence. &nbsp;Searching the burnt fields, checking every crevice and cranny for signs of life, had kept you occupied for days, allowing you to ignore the unpleasant conversation you had been&hellip; dreading is the wrong word, but you can&rsquo;t really think of a better one in its place. &nbsp;But now, with the survivors (or otherwise) found, there is nothing left to excuse you. &nbsp;You know what you have to do.</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">You sigh, openly. &nbsp;Such brooding isn&rsquo;t like you. You hadn&rsquo;t been-</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Wait a moment. &nbsp;You were about to brood about brooding.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Okay, time to nip this in the bud. &nbsp;You jam the rest of the tuber into your mouth, working at it as you hop down from your perch. &nbsp;Steady hands and strong jaws work in parallel, and before long, you drop back onto one of the crumbled walls of Eschaton. &nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">The trip to the Great Circle is a short one, but still manages to be unpleasant. &nbsp;Not just for the signs of deprivation and weary that still strike the Crag, there&rsquo;s also the simple fact that, for some reason, ever since the Extermination you have been&hellip; increasingly uncomfortable in confined spaces. &nbsp;Compared to the unbroken horizon of the Lower Plains, to have your sight constrained by artifice and construction just feels&hellip; well&hellip; constricting. &nbsp;However, as you finally walk into the familiar halls, such confinement gives way to pleasant nostalgia. Eschaton may be home to all Crag, but the Circle is Home to the Aggro.</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">The door before you is thick, set with iron bands, and you throw it open before you have any more opportunity to wax poetic about the deep seated portent behind it or whatever. &nbsp;However, your rapid entry leaves you unprepared for what you see.</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Echo of Blood, hugest of all the Aggro, sits in the dark, a single guttering candle lighting his personal quarters. &nbsp;Reflected in candlelight, you can see the bare flesh of his arms and chest, angry, red, warped and twisted. &nbsp;His right side, from his hand to his pectoral, is just one massive burn, blistered, blackened, the flesh even seeming to run in some places. &nbsp;Though bandaged in some places, most of the damage has been left exposed to the mountain air. &nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">In spite of yourself, you gasp.</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">If Echo&hellip; if Saltik&hellip; takes any offense at your shock, he shows no signs of it. &nbsp;Though seated on his bed, his andesite eyes are nearly level with yours, and all you can see in them is weariness. &nbsp;That, in and of itself, is more shocking than the wounds.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Finally, he chuckles, a low, grinding rumble.</span></p>
<p class="c3"><span class="c12 c23">&ldquo;Close the door, Embebi. &nbsp;Didn&rsquo;t your cladekeeper teach you better?&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">A soft smile settles on your face, and you chuckle alongside him, doing as he asks. &nbsp;Looking to overcome the initial awkwardness, you seek out his guest stool and kick it over to yourself.</span></p>
<p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c7 c15">&ldquo;Sorry to keep you waiting so long, sib. &nbsp;A lot of cleanup work to do down there. &nbsp;Ox before the cart, aff?&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">He says nothing, but you can feel some of his jocularity worn away. &nbsp;Right. &nbsp;Bad topic.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c7 c15">&ldquo;...Okay. &nbsp;So. &nbsp;Sitrep. Aar recon. Targs lowelf-&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Echo holds up his left hand. &nbsp; Though still burned, it is not nearly the mass of cauterized flesh his right is. </span></p>
<p class="c3"><span class="c23 c12">&ldquo;Keep it civil, sib. &nbsp;Details, not speed. &nbsp;Start with broad strokes. &nbsp;We&rsquo;ll fill in from there.&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c7 c15">&ldquo;Aff. &nbsp; Alright, starting from the beginning. &nbsp;You know the basics of the mission origin; Lowlander comes here, manages to see the Esteemed Elpahka, she manages to get some geoloc- some lowlander settlement locations off of the Lowlander, and then, for some reason, lets her go. &nbsp;By the way, I can partially confirm the other location we got; it looks like a separate&hellip; Tribe? Type? &nbsp;Let&rsquo;s go with type, of Elf lives there too. &nbsp;Kind of close, for my tastes.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c7 c15">Anyway. &nbsp;Journey was mostly nonsit. We arrive at the chosen encampment; it looks like the residents there, &ldquo;Blade Elves&rdquo;... you remember them&hellip; either claimed or constructed a sizeable fortification there. &nbsp;It&rsquo;s decent work for those without will. &nbsp;Crackable, but it&rsquo;d take a bit. &nbsp;Not that I think we&rsquo;ll need to. &nbsp;So far, they seem pretty content to remain there; they&rsquo;ve got an abundance of arable land, and do not want for nutrition- hence, all the &lsquo;potatoes&rsquo;, but the details on that come later.&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c3"><span class="c26 c12">&ldquo;Don&rsquo;t worry overmuch reporting on disposition yet. &nbsp;If we do need to engage, we would need more recent information in any case. &nbsp;</span><span class="c26 c5 c12">Broad</span><span class="c23 c12">&nbsp;sweeps, sib.&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c7 c15">&ldquo;Aff. Okay, broader. &nbsp;We reached the settlement. &nbsp;They informed us that they were hosting some kind of&hellip; they called it a &lsquo;pot-luck&rsquo;. &nbsp;There&rsquo;s no equivalent translation. &nbsp;Best comparison, various Elftype representatives come, give an offering of food to the hosts, and in return have an opportunity to interact with all of the other Elftypes. &nbsp;It seemed an extremely&hellip; informal arrangement. &nbsp;There were some perfunctory attempts at ritual, but it was mostly just a guideless scrum.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c7 c15">While there, I had the opportunity to observe some odd conduct, but nothing that particularly stood out as an immediate existential threat to Eschaton, or it&rsquo;s secrecy. &nbsp;The Layer, for her part, seemed to understand opsec enough to not blab that. Although&hellip;&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Fourth hell, this is the part you were&hellip; again, dreading was wrong. &nbsp;Anticipated being embarrassing? </span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">You sigh. Saltik raises one of his bushy eyebrows.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c7 c15">&ldquo;...I cannot claim to have witnessed her actions the whole time. &nbsp;I made a mistake. &nbsp;I can explain it, but it will require further details. &nbsp;They could be relevant to our current situation, at least?&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">He says nothing. &nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c7 c15">&ldquo;...During the event, I witnessed at least one attempt at Ritual that seemed sincere, though crude. &nbsp;A representative from an Elftype who call themselves the &ldquo;Fire Elves&rdquo; arrived, bearing challenge. &nbsp;She bore the Epithet &ldquo;Ashwalker&rdquo;, and challenged what seemed to be a Blade senret. &nbsp;Evidently, the trial was &lsquo;over the honor of their schools.&rsquo; &nbsp;Best guess, she was attempting to establish superiority of a fighting style? &nbsp;That&rsquo;s how she explained it to me, anyway. &nbsp;Err, she, being the Ashwalker. &nbsp;<br>The challenge was clumsy. &nbsp;Though there were declared Stakes, there was no Bid, and none moved to form a Circle of Equals. &nbsp;I did, of course, and so I actually observed what happened. &nbsp;Because there was no bid, both fought with full arm, but Ashwalker brought only her wholesome self, while the senret&hellip; Ehra, Holder of the ...something&hellip; Bloodname of Indrek, I think was his name&hellip; had not only a weapon of iron, but also, I noticed, armor. &nbsp;Obviously, the Ashwalker was felled by telling blow, succumbed as lowlanders are known to, and was recovered. &nbsp;Curiously, when recovered, they took the scar of the telling blow from her; I believe to chide her, as the whole challenge seemed to be met with an air of... &nbsp;well, disapproval by all joined. &nbsp;I figured this too harsh by far, and so felt moved to converse with her.&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c3"><span class="c23 c12">&ldquo;I do not wish to say it, but I believe you acted unwisely, sib. &nbsp;You Stalkers were always far removed from&hellip; interacting with the Lowlanders. &nbsp;From what I observed&hellip; and had inflicted upon me&hellip; they are unknowable. &nbsp;Alien. &nbsp;We cannot presume anything from familiar actions. It is possible for one to act in a familiar way, by unfamiliar motivations.&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">...You actually hadn&rsquo;t thought about that. &nbsp;You knew, to some degree, that Lowlanders would probably act differently, but you hadn&rsquo;t really considered how differently they would think. &nbsp;You just considered that their representatives to this potluck were likely to be&hellip; eccentric. &nbsp;But what if that was normal for them?</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c7 c15">&ldquo;Well, sib, if you thought that unwise, what follows is likely worth greater chastisement. &nbsp;You are correct, I was thinking of their actions as foolish; I felt that they had been poorly trained, or simply lax in their adherence to ritual. &nbsp;As such, when one of their number&hellip; I believe him to be some equivalent of theirs to the Bakshish, based on his professed skills&hellip; attempted to act disrespectfully to the Ashwalker and myself during our discussion, I felt it was an opportune time to demonstrate the superiority of Aggro Ritual.&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">You expected him to frown, or scoff, but surprisingly, he seems curious. &nbsp;Well, then. &nbsp;Not only Lowlanders are unknowable.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c7 c15">&ldquo;Being that he seemed to be a non-combatant&hellip; although he did wield a weapon, oddly&hellip; I made clear my intent to issue a Rite of Refusal. &nbsp;I hoped to quell his ego through a demonstration of Art. &nbsp;Unfortunately, a Blade who bore the Epithet of Warmaster General instructed that duals were to be held outside- curious she had not done so for the first one, but there must be some mad Lowlander reason for the distinction. &nbsp;Unfortunately, in so accepting this condition, I was separated from the Layer. &nbsp;I cannot account for her actions at that time.&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c3"><span class="c23 c12">&ldquo;I would not worry overmuch. &nbsp;It seems unlikely that the Layer could have done anything foolish in so little time. &nbsp;My interactions with her have painted her as a sane individual.&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c7 c15">&ldquo;I wish I could be so confident. &nbsp;It was during this absence that she brokered her deal with the Lowlanders to provide us with the nutrition we carried back. &nbsp;While I was not told the full details, I have inferred that this is not to be the last shipment; on the return, The Layer made many inquiries regarding the Aggro&rsquo;s upcoming need for Iron and Steel. &nbsp;I believe she intends to barter such for further nutrition.&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">At that, he grows quiet. &nbsp;His features sag. &nbsp;No discernable emotion crosses them. &nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Then, his gaze turns to look at his ruined arm. &nbsp;You know why it still seems wounded so, although the fire was many days past. &nbsp;He intends to heal this injury naturally, to let his body become accustomed to this new, scarred shape, so he may bear the mark of this firestorm forever. &nbsp;But does he intend it to be a mark of pride? Or one of shame?</span></p>
<p class="c3"><span class="c23 c12">&ldquo;I wish you had been here, sib. &nbsp;Few know those treacherous Lowlands as you and your Stalkers. &nbsp;Perhaps with your guidance, our exuberance could have been contained.</span></p>
<p class="c3"><span class="c23 c12">It seemed simple enough. &nbsp;We descended. &nbsp;We stripped. &nbsp;But the fauna were evasive. &nbsp;And even stripped of their leaves, the foliage, the forest concealed so much. &nbsp;With that out of the way, we could pursue them freely. &nbsp;Some creatures may outrun an Aggro, but none could outpace us.&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">He gazes into your eyes. &nbsp;You see pain there. &nbsp;You know it has nothing to do with his wounds.</span></p>
<p class="c3"><span class="c26 c12">&ldquo;We should have known that flame follows no ritual, respects no plan. &nbsp;But we did not consider this. &nbsp;We could not have known to. &nbsp;Without </span><span class="c26 c5 c12">The Tome</span><span class="c26 c12">, we had no guidance in the matter. &nbsp; At one time, that explanation could be used as an </span><span class="c5 c12 c26">Excuse.</span><span class="c23 c12">&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c16 c18">His face contorts into a rictus of rage. &nbsp;He slams his injured arm against his bedpost, and with a </span><span class="c16 c18 c5">crack</span><span>&nbsp;</span><span class="c2">that is deafening in the confined space, the post gives way. &nbsp;To avoid sprawling over as his bed collapses, he stands quickly, head nearly colliding with the ceiling.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">He slams the arm against the wall. &nbsp;This is sturdy enough to restrain his fury, but blisters burst and blood flows from the battered, burned limb. &nbsp;Once more, twice more, thrice more he strikes, leaving an impression of gore.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">Thankfully, this seems to have been enough. &nbsp;Pain of the body can overwhelm pain of the mind. &nbsp;Sometimes, it is a welcome replacement. &nbsp;Exhaustion floods his features. &nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">You take your hand off your kuthe. &nbsp;You will not need it today.</span></p>
<p class="c3"><span class="c23 c12">&ldquo;...Your Trial. &nbsp;The one with the Lowlander Bakshish. &nbsp;What was the result? &nbsp;You were victorious, quiaff?&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c7 c15">&ldquo;...Aff, sib, but I should not have been. &nbsp;Though I am skilled in my Art, rightfully prideful, the Lowlander was far from incapable. &nbsp;His tactics and methods were crude...rude&hellip; of ill attitude. &nbsp;But those Numbered saw nothing to object to. &nbsp;I was put off balance. &nbsp;He discovered a weak point, pursued it with fervor, and my riposte was clumsy. &nbsp;I broke meter. &nbsp;I even failed scheme, at the end. &nbsp;Victory should have been his, but for reasons I cannot imagine, he quit the Circle before telling blow. &nbsp;He shamed himself utterly, and yet he did so with the air of a man impatient and annoyed, not one fearful or disgra. &nbsp;&ldquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c16 c18">He grows quiet again. &nbsp;His oozing arm drips audibly on the flagstones. </span></p>
<p class="c3"><span class="c23 c12">&ldquo;We cannot keep doing this, sib. &nbsp;The Aggro cannot. &nbsp;I cannot. &nbsp;We cannot keep blundering into the wild unknown, unguided, untrained, and unheeding of the dangers ahead. &nbsp;We promised ourselves after the Extermination that we would never be found wanting again. &nbsp;We must now consider what it will actually take to stick to that promise.</span></p>
<p class="c3"><span class="c23 c12">We cannot keep beating against a flame that will not turn. &nbsp;We are found. &nbsp;Whether by this Seeker, whether by the Layer&rsquo;s words, whether by curious souls, the truth is that we can no longer rely on our greatest shield. &nbsp;It would just turn into another exercise where you must kill everyone who notices you are killing everyone.</span></p>
<p class="c3"><span class="c26 c12">If we must be found, if the Lowlanders must come, then we- the Aggro, the Crag, everyone- cannot afford to be ignorant of them any longer. &nbsp;And without </span><span class="c26 c5 c12">The Tome</span><span class="c23 c12">, the only ones who know about Lowlanders&hellip; are Lowlanders.&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">You feel excitement coursing through you. &nbsp;You had never imagined that the conversation could go in this direction. &nbsp;You would never. &nbsp;expected such words. &nbsp;Not from Saltik. &nbsp;Not from the Echo of Blood.</span></p>
<p class="c3"><span class="c23 c12">&ldquo;Sib. Embebi. &nbsp;I do not know what plans the Layer&hellip; or, indeed, the Esteemed&hellip; have laid out for these Lowlanders. &nbsp;Whatever it is, you must become indispensable to it. &nbsp;We must have knowledge. &nbsp;We must have foundation. &nbsp;We must have guidance. &nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="c3"><span class="c26 c12">For so long, I have tried to guide the Aggro back to The Path. Back to our glory. &nbsp;Back to where we </span><span class="c26 c5 c12">once</span><span class="c23 c12">&nbsp;belonged. </span></p>
<p class="c3"><span class="c23 c12">The Path is Sundered. &nbsp;I now accept that. &nbsp;Now&hellip; we must Trod Uncertainty.&rdquo;</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">...Oh.</span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">You didn&rsquo;t expect that, either.</span></p>
<hr><p class="c1"><span class="c2"></span></p>
<p class="c6"><span class="c2">The expanse of Eschaton sweeps beneath you. &nbsp;From here, the Pagoda of the Esteemed, it stretches in all directions. &nbsp;Close by, life still hums in the streets in spite of want and deprivation. &nbsp;Further out is little more than bones and ruin, still abandoned after all these years, still an eventual project on your mental list. &nbsp;You had thought of those ruins as an unfortunate result of necessary triage, the dead left so that the living could still be tended to. &nbsp;An unfortunate charnel circle made of shattered stone and broken futures.</span></p>
